@keboliu @Junchao-Mellanox 
To my understanding, this has no impact on `show platform psustatus`. This change should only effect `show platform temperature` as the modification changes how temperatures are stored within the temperature DB. Specifically making it 1) so that if a device is removed during runtime (in a fixed platform) that the temperature sensors associated with it are not left stale within the DB, in the exact same manner as is done already within modular chassis and 2) so that if a PSU is disabled/turned off during runtime but is still present in the chassis, that it's sensors are not included in the temperature DB either.

I have confirmed that this DOES pass `platform_tests/cli/test_show_platform.py::test_show_platform_temperature[mth64-m5-2] PASSED ` and the behavior in the test case for `test_show_platform_psustatus` is also unchanged from before changes are applied. Additionally, this change should not warrant/require any changes to the CLI reference as the overall functionality and display format of `show platform temperature` remains completely untouched. To reiterate from above, all this change does is change the behavior of when sensors are removed/included from the temperature database. All other components (especially its display and formatting) of `show platform temperature` remain unchanged.

@keboliu , I think the purpose of "show platform temperature" is to display all temperatures from components that are "present".  It absolutely makes no sense to display components that are not even present.  It is up to the user to decide whether they want to populate all the PSU slots or just keep it at minimum (to save cost perhaps, or in the middle of RMA replacement). Redundancy is not a must especially if the device purpose is not mission critical for the user.  
So for components that are not present we should make the change and not keep them in the stateDB.  I don't think the current behavior is correct and we should fix it with this PR.

@gregoryboudreau, I also do not agree to remove BAD PSUs that are "present" from the stateDB from being displayed by "show platform temperature". We must trust the "Presence" signal and still attempt to read out the sensors. We don't know if we can trust the sensor data if the PSU is bad.  But it does provide some useful info with readout that raise concerns in case it went bad or in the process of becoming bad with temperature swings read out so that it allows us to detect and perform troubleshooting/RMA before it totally goes dead.  It could be that it got declared as "BAD" way too early or falsely and in that case as long as the PSU is "present", the temperature data can provide some usefulness. Temperature changes is a good way to provide alert signals.  Also, this provides one additional signal that we can use besides totally depended on "show platform psustatus" to detect the problem.  I do not think all bad PSU cases will lead to no temperature sensor can be read out.  As long as the component is "present" we should try to read out the temperatures from it.  Can you change the PR to restore the readout for PSUs that are "present"?

Thanks!

